{"entries":[{"caption":"Probability and Odds: A Clinical Lookup Table","key":"tbl-prob-odds","order":{"number":2,"section":[5,6,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Diagnostic Cascade: How Probability Climbs with Each Piece of Evidence. This is what you do every day — Bayes’ theorem formalises it.","key":"fig-diagnostic-cascade","order":{"number":1,"section":[5,3,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Step-by-Step Bayesian Updates for SLE Diagnosis","key":"tbl-sle-updates","order":{"number":3,"section":[5,8,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Three Probability Fallacies and Their Clinical Consequences. Recognising these errors is essential for safe diagnostic reasoning.","key":"fig-three-fallacies","order":{"number":14,"section":[5,9,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Natural Frequency Tree: Dengue NS1 Test During Monsoon (n = 1000 febrile patients). PPV = 128 / (128 + 43) = 75%. Three-quarters of positive tests are true dengue.","key":"fig-dengue-monsoon-tree","order":{"number":6,"section":[5,7,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Sequential Bayesian Updates in Diagnosing SLE. Each clinical and laboratory finding shifts the probability — no single test ‘diagnoses’ SLE. The cascade IS the diagnosis.","key":"fig-sle-cascade","order":{"number":10,"section":[5,8,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Addition Rule: Why you can’t just add prevalences when conditions overlap. The 6% with both diabetes AND hypertension would be double-counted.","key":"fig-venn-addition","order":{"number":2,"section":[5,4,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Same Test, Different Yield: The CBC ordered by faculty has higher PPV because the pre-test probability is higher. This is conditional probability in action.","key":"fig-cbc-comparison","order":{"number":4,"section":[5,5,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Base Rate Fallacy: Why ‘95% Accurate’ Doesn’t Mean ‘95% Chance of Disease’. At 2% prevalence, most positive results are false alarms.","key":"fig-base-rate-fallacy","order":{"number":13,"section":[5,9,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"PPV vs Prevalence for the Dengue NS1 Test. The same test is clinically useful during monsoon (PPV 75%) but misleading in January (PPV 7%). The test didn’t change — the clinical context did.","key":"fig-ppv-prevalence-dengue","order":{"number":8,"section":[5,7,5,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Why Two Positive Blood Cultures Are Much More Convincing Than One. The multiplication rule shows that dual contamination is extremely unlikely if bottles are independently drawn.","key":"fig-blood-culture","order":{"number":3,"section":[5,4,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Ruling Out PE: A Downward Bayesian Cascade. Wells score and D-dimer together bring the probability low enough to safely avoid CT angiography.","key":"fig-pe-ruling-out","order":{"number":12,"section":[5,8,5,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Mammography Screening Dilemma: Of 78 positive mammograms, only 9 are true cancer. PPV = 11.5%. This is the example that revolutionised understanding of Bayesian reasoning in medicine.","key":"fig-mammography-tree","order":{"number":9,"section":[5,7,6,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Probability Waterfall for SLE Diagnosis. Green bars show increases from each piece of evidence. The steeper the rise, the more informative that evidence was.","key":"fig-sle-waterfall","order":{"number":11,"section":[5,8,4,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Two Directions of Conditional Probability in Diagnosis","key":"tbl-two-directions","order":{"number":1,"section":[5,5,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Probability and Odds Are Two Representations of the Same Uncertainty. Note: odds scale is non-linear — small changes in probability near 0% or 100% correspond to large changes in odds.","key":"fig-prob-odds-curve","order":{"number":5,"section":[5,6,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Module 4 Summary: The complete framework connecting clinical reasoning to probability theory.","key":"fig-module-summary","order":{"number":15,"section":[5,10,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Same NS1 Test in January (n = 1000 febrile patients). PPV drops from 75% to just 8%! Most positive results are now false alarms.","